A/B Testing on Email Delivery¶

Ming Zhao
May, 2022

Goals¶

  • To evaluate the effect of daily email delivery (treatment) vs. twice-a-week email delivery (control) on open and conversion rates

Methods¶

  • One-to-one greedy propensity score matching
  • Two-sample t-Test of proportions

Findings¶

  • Daily delivery has a higher open rate than twice-a-week delivery
  • Daily delivery has a higher funding rate than twice-a-week delivery

Outline¶

  • Data Preparation
    • Data Loading and Cleaning
    • Data Merging and Exploring
  • A/B Testing
  • Propensity Score Matching + A/B Testing
    • Matching Implementation
      • Estimate the propensity score. This is the probability (logistic regression) that an observation is treated or not. Its logit value is also calculated.
      • Perform Nearest Neighbor matching (greedy matching) within a specified caliper distance strategy. For each treated sample, identify an untreated sample with similar logit propensity score. The matching is 1-to-1 without replacement.
    • Matching Review
      • Once matching is performed, we review the balance of the X variables to assess their balance
    • Average Treatment Effect
      • Estimate the impact of treatment.

PSM Assumptions¶

  • Unconfoundedness assumption: Selection on treatment (i.e. T) should be solely based on observable characteristics (i.e. X). Assuming there is no selection bias from unobserved characteristics. It is not possible to prove the validity of this unconfoundedness assumption.

  • Common support: Observations with similar characteristics are present in both treatment and control groups.

  • Conditional independence assumption: There are no unobserved differences correlated to potential outcomes once we have controlled for certain observable characteristics.

A/B testing¶

Original Dataset¶

  • Significant differences in opening and funding rates
In [31]:
df.groupby(["treatment"])[["open", "fund"]].agg(["mean", "var", "count"])
# daily delivery is the control: 1
# twice-a-week delivery is the treatment: 0
Out[31]:
open fund
mean var count mean var count
treatment
0 0.503348 0.249990 239999 0.031117 0.030149 239999
1 0.508371 0.249931 240000 0.032162 0.031128 240000
  • OPENING

$H_0: P_D = P_W$
(daily delivery has the same opening rate as twice-a-week delivery)

$H_a: P_D \neq P_W$
(daily delivery does not have the same opening rate as twice-a-week delivery)

$p-value=0.000<0.05$, so we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that daily delivery and twice-a-week delivery do not have the same opening rate.

In [32]:
t, p = stats.ttest_ind(
    df[df['treatment']==1]['open'],
    df[df['treatment']==0]['open'],
    equal_var=False, # If True (default), perform a standard independent 2 sample test
                     # If False, perform Welch’s t-test
    alternative='two-sided'
)
print("The t-value is %0.3f and the p-value is %0.4f." % (t, p))

The t-value is 3.480 and the p-value is 0.0005.
  • FUNDING

$H_0: P_D = P_W$
(daily delivery has the same funding rate as twice-a-week delivery)

$H_a: P_D \neq P_W$
(daily delivery does not have the same funding rate as twice-a-week delivery)

$p-value=0.038<0.05$, so we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that daily delivery and twice-a-week delivery do not have the same funding rate.

In [33]:
t, p = stats.ttest_ind(
    df[df['treatment']==1]['fund'],
    df[df['treatment']==0]['fund'],
    equal_var=False, # If True (default), perform a standard independent 2 sample test
                     # If False, perform Welch’s t-test
    alternative='two-sided'
)
print("The t-value is %0.3f and the p-value is %0.4f." % (t, p))

The t-value is 2.070 and the p-value is 0.0385.
  • OPENING

$H_0: P_D < P_W$
(daily delivery has a lower opening rate than twice-a-week delivery)

$H_a: P_D > P_W$
(daily delivery has a higher opening rate than twice-a-week delivery)

$p-value=0.000<0.05$, so we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that daily delivery has a higher opening rate than twice-a-week delivery.

In [34]:
t, p = stats.ttest_ind(
    df[df['treatment']==1]['open'],
    df[df['treatment']==0]['open'],
    equal_var=False, 
    alternative='greater' #‘greater’: the mean of the distribution underlying the first sample is greater than the mean of the distribution underlying the second sample
)
print("The t-value is %0.3f and the p-value is %0.4f." % (t, p))

The t-value is 3.480 and the p-value is 0.0003.
  • FUNDING

$H_0: P_D < P_W$
(daily delivery has a lower funding rate than twice-a-week delivery)

$H_a: P_D > P_W$
(daily delivery has a higher funding rate than twice-a-week delivery)

$p-value=0.019<0.05$, so we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that daily delivery has a higher funding rate than twice-a-week delivery.

args = ["approved_within6M_flag", "link_flag", 
        "recent_activity_flag(20days)", "5day_trade_flag"]

def plot(arg):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(10, 6), sharex=True)
    fig.suptitle('Comparison of {} split by treatment status.'.format(arg))
    sns.kdeplot(data = psm.predicted_data, x = arg, hue = 'treatment', ax = ax[0]).set(title='Density before matching')
    sns.kdeplot(data = psm_df, x = arg, hue = 'treatment',  ax = ax[1]).set(title='Density after matching')
    plt.subplots_adjust(wspace = 0.3)
    plt.show()

for arg in args:
    plot(arg)

att_open = treated_open - treated_counterfactual_open
print('The Average Treatment Effect (ATT) for the openning rate: {:.4f}'.format(att_open))
att_fund = treated_fund - treated_counterfactual_fund
print('The Average Treatment Effect (ATT) for the funding rate: {:.4f}'.format(att_fund))

The Average Treatment Effect (ATT) for the openning rate: 0.0318
The Average Treatment Effect (ATT) for the funding rate: 0.0158
  • OPENING

$H_0: P_D < P_W$
(daily delivery has a lower opening rate than twice-a-week delivery)

$H_a: P_D > P_W$
(daily delivery has a higher opening rate than twice-a-week delivery)

$p-value=0.000<0.05$, so we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that daily delivery has a higher opening rate than twice-a-week delivery.

In [69]:
t, p = stats.ttest_ind(
    psm_df[psm_df['treatment']==1]['open'],
    psm_df[psm_df['treatment']==0]['open'],
    equal_var=False, 
    alternative='greater' #‘greater’: the mean of the distribution underlying the first sample is greater than the mean of the distribution underlying the second sample
)
print("The t-value is %0.3f and the p-value is %0.4f." % (t, p))

The t-value is 3.901 and the p-value is 0.0000.
  • FUNDING

$H_0: P_D < P_W$
(daily delivery has a lower funding rate than twice-a-week delivery)

$H_a: P_D > P_W$
(daily delivery has a higher funding rate than twice-a-week delivery)

$p-value=0.0000<0.05$, so we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that daily delivery has a higher funding rate than twice-a-week delivery.
